{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"body":"PASS-1 review [T1 — prior-art / novel-architecture justification]: CLEAN, no findings.\n\nAffirmations:\n- No T1 bright-line fires that demands a prior-art search: this is a telemetry reinstatement, not a new external integration, unfamiliar dependency, security/auth surface, novel architecture, or migration. The latency-split mechanism (per-step monotonic wall-clock, aggregated by step id/kind into a det vs LLM tier) is a well-trodden instrumentation pattern needing no prior-art justification.\n- (a) Prior art is explicitly considered, not reinvented: the plan deliberately reconstructs the EXISTING db7b AC5 contract (coverage['metrics'] = {det_ms, llm_ms, total_ms, llm_calls, claim_path}), states claim_path \"matching the db7b dict exactly,\" and notes the llm_calls proxy \"Mirrors run_review's coverage-derived proxy.\" It anchors to the retired run_review producer rather than designing a fresh shape.\n- (b) No novel pattern to justify; moreover the plan documents the SOURCE DECISION (resolving the AC's two candidates — step timings for the tier split, finder criteria_count for the llm_calls proxy), which is exactly the design-choice rationale (b) looks for.\n- (c) The load-bearing capability assertion (interpreter records per-step duration_ms) is its own first AC and is verifiable in-tree (interpreter.py records duration_ms on leaf and batch steps; gate_dispatch reconstructs from rec.steps); the claim_path \"structural marker (local HMAC verify)\" is a marker, not an unverified library-capability claim.\n\nNot a finding — recorded as positive affirmation per coaching spec."},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"COMMENT","timestamp":1782546175569600001,"uuid":"0b8c82e3-6c81-4108-9ae6-0156c3b6bad0"}